30/10/19, 1:23â€¯pm - ManasviğŸ’©: since a lot of people  wanted more  dp problems ,i will suggest few more

0)https://www.interviewbit.com/problems/burst-balloons/ (very easy )
1)https://www.spoj.com/problems/FARIDA/ (very easy)
2)https://vjudge.net/problem/UVA-10359 (very easy, tiling dp)
3)https://vjudge.net/problem/UVA-10003 (very easy, also find the time complexity of your solution)
4)https://cses.fi/problemset/task/1744/ (easy , somewhat  similar to above one , but only bottom up solution passes and top-down gives TLE )

//lis(longest increasing subsequence) is an important sub topic and there are few variations to it
5)https://www.codechef.com/problems/PEC005 ( easy , longest increasing subsequence(lis)  expected time complexity = O(N*N))
6)https://www.spoj.com/problems/LPIS/ (similar to above , lis )

//for below two problems actual time complexity required is O(N*logN) and is not taught till now , but if u can come up with some O(N*N) logic then it's also fine.
7)https://vjudge.net/problem/LightOJ-1421 (easy-medium , variation of lis , actual time complexity required is O(N*logN) but O(N*N) is fine for you people)
8)https://www.spoj.com/problems/LIS2/ (medium , variation of lis ,actual time complexity required is O(N*logN) but O(N*N) is fine for you people)

9)https://www.spoj.com/problems/MIXTURES/en/ (easy-medium)
10)https://vjudge.net/problem/LightOJ-1326 (medium-hard , counting )
11)https://www.spoj.com/problems/SCUBADIV/en/ (medium , knapsack)
12) Given an array of N integers , Consider all the subsequences of this array and for each subsequence find the sum of elements chosen and  push this sum into a
new array and sort it in ascending order. (medium )
sub task1:
there's only one query in it and this query contains a number K , and u have to report the Kth element in this new list.(use 1-indexing)
sub task2:
There are Q queries (Q&lt;=1e5) and for each query  a single number K is given , and u have to report the Kth element in this new list.(use 1-indexing)

 sample test case :
 //for sub task1
 input:
 3//this is N
 1 2 1 //this is array
 4 //this is K

 output:
 2 // 4th element in this new array is 2

 explanation:

//for each subsequence find it's sum and push it into a new array so
 in this case the new array will be {1,1,2,2,3,3,4} and we are given K=4 so the fourth element is 2

 note: with this we have done enough variety of dp problems, we can discuss solutions of these problems in next two classes.

06/10/20, 1:48â€¯am - mehul mathur: # Hotel Quokka Database CLI
A command line interface that accesses a mysql database named 'HOTEL_QUOKKA'.
- The contents of the Database HOTEL_QUOKKA are dumped and saved in newt.sql file with some test values in the tables. To start a mysql environment with that database run the command:
```sh
mysql -u <username> -p 
```
- And then source the file inside the mysql environment by:
```sh
source newt.sql
```

 - Exit mysql environment and download the python file HotelQuokka.py. Run it as
 ```sh
 python3 HotelQuokka.py
 ```
This will lead you to a CLI interface, where on entering your username and mysql password, you can begin to interact with the Database. 
Run any commands as presented to you. They have been divided into requirements of a guest and requirements related to the staff

from random import randrange
import random
import sys, os

bpy.ops.object.select_all(action='SELECT')
bpy.ops.object.delete(use_global=False, confirm=False)

bpy.ops.mesh.primitive_cube_add()
bpy.ops.transform.resize(value=(1.2, 0.2, 3.5))
bpy.ops.transform.translate(value=(0,-5,0.0))

bpy.ops.mesh.primitive_cube_add()
bpy.ops.transform.resize(value=(1.2, 0.2, 3.5))
bpy.ops.transform.translate(value=(0,5,0.0))

bpy.ops.mesh.primitive_cube_add()
bpy.ops.transform.resize(value=(1.5,5, 0.1))
bpy.ops.transform.translate(value=(0,0,-1))

bpy.ops.mesh.primitive_cube_add()
bpy.ops.transform.resize(value=(1.5,5, 0.1))
bpy.ops.transform.translate(value=(0,0,2))

bpy.ops.transform.resize(value=(.8,.8, 0.8))

06/04/21, 10:46â€¯am - mehul mathur: <Media omitted>
06/04/21, 12:51â€¯pm - mehul mathur: A_fp = open("A_matrix.txt" , 'w')
A = np.zeros((len(TRANSITION_TABLE) , len(R)))
column_number = 0
for state in TRANSITION_TABLE.keys():
    for action in TRANSITION_TABLE[state].keys():
        if action == "NONE":
            A[STATE_NUMS[state]][column_number] = 1.0
        else:
            for nbr , probability in TRANSITION_TABLE[state][action]:
                A[STATE_NUMS[state]][column_number] += probability
                A[STATE_NUMS[nbr]][column_number] -= probability
        
        A_fp.write('COLUMN FOR STATE {} AND ACTION {}\n'.format(state , action))
        A_fp.write(str(A[: , column_number]))
        A_fp.write("\n\n")
        # print(column_number)
        column_number += 1

A_fp.close()

11/04/21, 12:22â€¯am - Pooja: A more recently developed nucleotide-level BLAST program called MegaBLAST (7) is about 10 times faster than â€œblastnâ€ but is designed to align sequences that are nearly identical, differing by only a few percent from one another. MegaBLAST allows the rapid mapping of a transcript onto a typical 3 billion base mammalian genome in seconds, and is useful for processing large batches of sequences. A refinement of MegaBLAST, known as discontiguous MegaBLAST, uses a discontiguous template to define an initial â€œwordâ€ in which characters in some positions, such as those in the wobble base position of codons, need not match. Discontiguous MegaBLAST allows rapid cross-species mappings involving coding regions in cases where species differences in codon usage would prevent alignments using the original MegaBLAST program.

11/04/21, 1:15â€¯am - Pooja: # Q5.

i. 

- Uniprot size - consists of two sections Swiss-Prot ( contains 542,782 sequence entries )  and TrEMBL ( contains 54,247,468 sequence entries ).
- GenBank size - contains over 6.25 trillion base pairs from over 1.6 billion nucleotide sequences.

Number of matrix cells required for a DP between two sequences of length n and m, is n*m, as it requires a matrix F which is of dimensions n*m. For each DP run, the time required is $O(nm)$.

For a query sequence of length 1000 bases, the time would be size * O(1000*m) where m is the size of each protein sequence in the UniProt Database. 

ii.

Human Chr 1 (size : 248*10^6) and query sequence of 1000 bases - memory requirement : $O(284*10^6 * 10^3)$.

Human Chr 1 (size : 248*10^6) and Chr 1 of Mouse ~195Mbp - memory requirement : $O(284*10^6 * 195*10^6)$.

14/09/21, 11:00â€¯am - Pooja: ```def get_tf(self, posting):
        sel = 'id'
        prev = 0
        dic = defaultdict()
        for i in range(len(posting)):
            if posting[i].isdigit() or (posting[i]>='a' and posting[i]<='f'):
                continue
            dic[sel] = int(posting[prev:i], 16)
            sel = posting[i]
            prev = i+1
        dic[sel] = int(posting[prev:len(posting)], 16) 
        tf = 0
        for key in dic.keys():
            if key == 'id':
                continue
            tf += self.weights[key] * dic[key]
        return tf```
14/09/21, 11:02â€¯am - mehul mathur: bro
14/09/21, 11:02â€¯am - mehul mathur: i dont see this happening lollll
14/09/21, 11:04â€¯am - ManasviğŸ’©: ```
def parse(self, posting):
        sel = 'id'
        prev = 0
        dic = defaultdict()
        for i in range(len(posting)):
            if posting[i].isdigit() or (posting[i]>='a' and posting[i]<='f'):
                continue
            dic[sel] = int(posting[prev:i], 16)
            sel = posting[i]
            prev = i+1
        dic[sel] = int(posting[prev:len(posting)], 16) 
        return dic

```

16/10/21, 1:56â€¯pm - mehul mathur: ```
def get_median(LO , HI):
  if len(LO) > len(HI):
    return (LO[0] * -1)
  else:
    return ((LO[0] * -1) + HI[0])/2

def see_heap(heap_arr , mx=False):
  temp = []
  temp[:] = heap_arr
  while temp:
    if mx:
      print(-1 * heapq.heappop(temp))
    else:
      print(heapq.heappop(temp))

def spatial_filter_median(k , im):
  new_im = np.copy(im)

  LO_HEAP = []
  HI_HEAP = []
  INVALID = [0]*256

  cent = ((k//2) , (k//2))
  row = 0
  col = 0

  for r in range(-(k//2) , (k//2)+1):
    for c in range(-(k//2) , (k//2)+1):
      if row + r >= 0 and row + r < im.shape[0] and col + c >= 0 and col + c < im.shape[1]:
        pixel_val = im[row+r][col+c]
      else:
        pixel_val = 0
      
      heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , -1 * pixel_val)
      heapq.heappush(HI_HEAP , -1 * heapq.heappop(LO_HEAP))
      if len(HI_HEAP) > len(LO_HEAP):
        heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , heapq.heappop(HI_HEAP) * -1)
  
  while row < im.shape[0]:

    new_im[row][col] = get_median(LO_HEAP , HI_HEAP)
    if not ((row%2 == 0 and col == im.shape[1]-1) or (row%2 == 1 and col == 0)):
      if row%2 == 0:
        for r in range(-(k//2) , (k//2)+1):
          #remove_add
          balance = 0

          #remove
          if row + r >= 0 and row + r < im.shape[0] and col - (k//2) >= 0 and col - (k//2) < im.shape[1]:
            out_num = im[row+r][col - (k//2)]
          else:
            out_num = 0
          
          if out_num <= (LO_HEAP[0] * -1):
            balance -= 1
          else:
            balance += 1
          
          INVALID[out_num] += 1

          #add
          if row + r >= 0 and row + r < im.shape[0] and col + 1 + (k//2) >= 0 and col + 1 + (k//2) < im.shape[1]:
            in_num = im[row+r][col + 1 + (k//2)]
          else:
            in_num = 0
          
          if LO_HEAP and in_num <= (LO_HEAP[0] * -1):
            balance += 1
            heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , -1 * in_num)
          else:
            balance -= 1
            heapq.heappush(HI_HEAP , in_num)
          
          #balance out
          if balance < 0:
            heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , heapq.heappop(HI_HEAP) * -1)
            balance += 1
          elif balance > 0:
            heapq.heappush(HI_HEAP , heapq.heappop(LO_HEAP) * -1)
            balance -= 1
          
          #lazy remove
          while INVALID[LO_HEAP[0] * -1] > 0:
            INVALID[LO_HEAP[0] * -1] -= 1
            heapq.heappop(LO_HEAP)
          
          while HI_HEAP and INVALID[HI_HEAP[0]] > 0:
            INVALID[HI_HEAP[0]] -= 1
            heapq.heappop(HI_HEAP)
          
        col += 1
      
      else:
        for r in range(-(k//2) , (k//2)+1):
          #remove_add
          balance = 0

          #remove
          if row + r >= 0 and row + r < im.shape[0] and col + (k//2) >= 0 and col + (k//2) < im.shape[1]:
            out_num = im[row+r][col + (k//2)]
          else:
            out_num = 0
          
          if out_num <= (LO_HEAP[0] * -1):
            balance -= 1
          else:
            balance += 1
          
          INVALID[out_num] += 1

          #add
          if row + r >= 0 and row + r < im.shape[0] and col - 1 - (k//2) >= 0 and col - 1 - (k//2) < im.shape[1]:
            in_num = im[row+r][col - 1 - (k//2)]
          else:
            in_num = 0
          
          if LO_HEAP and in_num <= (LO_HEAP[0] * -1):
            balance += 1
            heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , -1 * in_num)
          else:
            balance -= 1
            heapq.heappush(HI_HEAP , in_num)
          
          #balance out
          if balance < 0:
            heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , heapq.heappop(HI_HEAP) * -1)
            balance += 1
          elif balance > 0:
            heapq.heappush(HI_HEAP , heapq.heappop(LO_HEAP) * -1)
            balance -= 1
          
          #lazy remove
          while INVALID[LO_HEAP[0] * -1] > 0:
            INVALID[LO_HEAP[0] * -1] -= 1
            heapq.heappop(LO_HEAP)
          
          while HI_HEAP and INVALID[HI_HEAP[0]] > 0:
            INVALID[HI_HEAP[0]] -= 1
            heapq.heappop(HI_HEAP)
          
        col -= 1
      
      
    else:
      if row == im.shape[0]-1:
        row += 1
        continue
      
      for c in range(-(k//2) , (k//2)+1):
        #remove_add
        balance = 0

        #remove
        if row - (k//2) >= 0 and row - (k//2) < im.shape[0] and col + c >= 0 and col + c < im.shape[1]:
          out_num = im[row - (k//2)][col + c]
        else:
          out_num = 0
        
        if out_num <= (LO_HEAP[0] * -1):
          balance -= 1
        else:
          balance += 1
        
        INVALID[out_num] += 1

        #add
        if row + (k//2) + 1 >= 0 and row + (k//2) + 1 < im.shape[0] and col + c >= 0 and col + c < im.shape[1]:
          in_num = im[row + (k//2) + 1][col + c]
        else:
          in_num = 0
        
        if LO_HEAP and in_num <= (LO_HEAP[0] * -1):
          balance += 1
          heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , -1 * in_num)
        else:
          balance -= 1
          heapq.heappush(HI_HEAP , in_num)
        
        #balance out
        if balance < 0:
          heapq.heappush(LO_HEAP , heapq.heappop(HI_HEAP) * -1)
          balance += 1
        elif balance > 0:
          heapq.heappush(HI_HEAP , heapq.heappop(LO_HEAP) * -1)
          balance -= 1
        
        #lazy remove
        while INVALID[LO_HEAP[0] * -1] > 0:
          INVALID[LO_HEAP[0] * -1] -= 1
          heapq.heappop(LO_HEAP)
        
        while HI_HEAP and INVALID[HI_HEAP[0]] > 0:
          INVALID[HI_HEAP[0]] -= 1
          heapq.heappop(HI_HEAP)

      row += 1
  
  return new_im
```

import dlib
 
webcam = False
cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0)
detector = dlib.get_frontal_face_detector()

def empty(a):
    pass
cv2.namedWindow("BGR")
cv2.resizeWindow("BGR",640,240)
cv2.createTrackbar("Blue","BGR",153,255,empty)
cv2.createTrackbar("Green","BGR",0,255,empty)
cv2.createTrackbar("Red","BGR",137,255,empty)
 
def createBox(img,points,scale=5,masked= False,cropped= True):
    if masked:
        mask = np.zeros_like(img)

import dlib
import cv2
 
webcam = False
cap = cv2.VideoCapture(0)
detector = dlib.get_frontal_face_detector()
predictor = dlib.shape_predictor("shape_predictor_68_face_landmarks.dat")
 
def empty(a):
    pass
cv2.namedWindow("BGR")
cv2.resizeWindow("BGR",640,240)
cv2.createTrackbar("Blue","BGR",153,255,empty)
cv2.createTrackbar("Green","BGR",0,255,empty)
cv2.createTrackbar("Red","BGR",137,255,empty)
 
def createBox(img,points,scale=5,masked= False,cropped= True):
    if masked:
        mask = np.zeros_like(img)
        mask = cv2.fillPoly(mask,[points],(255,255,255))
        img = cv2.bitwise_and(img,mask)
        #cv2.imshow('Mask',mask)
 
    if cropped:
        bbox = cv2.boundingRect(points)
        x, y, w, h = bbox
        imgCrop = img[y:y+h,x:x+w]
        imgCrop = cv2.resize(imgCrop,(0,0),None,scale,scale)
        cv2.imwrite("Mask.jpg",imgCrop)
        return imgCrop
    else:
        return mask
 
while True:
 
    if webcam: success,img = cap.read()
    else: img = cv2.imread('face.jpeg')
    img = cv2.resize(img,(0,0),None,0.6,0.6)
    imgOriginal = img.copy()
    imgGray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
 
    faces = detector(imgOriginal)
    for face in faces:
        x1,y1 = face.left(),face.top()
        x2,y2 = face.right(),face.bottom()
        #imgOriginal=cv2.rectangle(imgOriginal, (x1, y1), (x2, y2), (0, 255, 0), 2)
        landmarks = predictor(imgGray, face)
        myPoints =[]
        for n in range(68):
            x = landmarks.part(n).x
            y = landmarks.part(n).y
            myPoints.append([x,y])
            #cv2.circle(imgOriginal, (x, y), 5, (50,50,255),cv2.FILLED)
            #cv2.putText(imgOriginal,str(n),(x,y-10),cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_COMPLEX_SMALL,0.8,(0,0,255),1)
        #print(myPoints)
        if len(myPoints) != 0:
            try:
                myPoints = np.array(myPoints)
                imgEyeBrowLeft = createBox(img, myPoints[17:22])
                imgEyeBrowRight = createBox(img, myPoints[22:27])
                imgNose = createBox(img, myPoints[27:36])
                imgLeftEye = createBox(img, myPoints[36:42])
                imgRightEye = createBox(img, myPoints[42:48])
                imgLips = createBox(img, myPoints[48:61])
                # cv2.imshow('Left Eyebrow', imgEyeBrowLeft)
                # cv2.imshow('Right Eyebrow',imgEyeBrowRight)
                # cv2.imshow('Nose',imgNose)
                # cv2.imshow('Left Eye',imgLeftEye)
                # cv2.imshow('Right Eye', imgRightEye)
                cv2.imshow('Lips', imgLips)
 
                maskLips = createBox(img, myPoints[48:61],masked = True,cropped=False)
                
                imgColorLips = np.zeros_like(maskLips)
                b = cv2.getTrackbarPos("Blue", "BGR")
                g = cv2.getTrackbarPos("Green", "BGR")
                r = cv2.getTrackbarPos("Red", "BGR")
 
                imgColorLips[:] = b,g,r
                imgColorLips = cv2.bitwise_and(maskLips,imgColorLips)
                imgColorLips = cv2.GaussianBlur(imgColorLips,(7,7),10)

                black_img  = np.zeros_like(imgOriginal)

                imgOriginalGray = cv2.cvtColor(imgOriginal,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
                imgOriginalGray = cv2.cvtColor(imgOriginalGray, cv2.COLOR_GRAY2BGR)
                imgColorLips = cv2.addWeighted(imgOriginalGray ,1,imgColorLips,0.4,0)
                cv2.imshow('BGR', imgColorLips)
 
            except:
                pass
 
    cv2.imshow("Originial", imgOriginal)
    cv2.waitKey(1)

27/11/21, 3:10â€¯am - mehul mathur: ```
import numpy as np
import dlib
import cv2


def draw_lines(image, points):

    for index in range(1,len(points)):
        start_point = tuple(points[index - 1])
        end_point = tuple(points[index])

        color = (255,255,255)
        thickness = 3

        image = cv2.line(image, start_point, end_point, color, thickness)

    return image


def feature_Detection(image_path):

    detector = dlib.get_frontal_face_detector()
    predictor = dlib.shape_predictor("shape_predictor_68_face_landmarks.dat")
    

    image = cv2.imread(image_path)
    imageGray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

    face = detector(image)[0]
    landmarks = predictor(imageGray, face)
    myPoints = []

    for n in range(68):
        x = landmarks.part(n).x
        y = landmarks.part(n).y
        myPoints.append([x,y])


    final_image = np.zeros(image.shape)

    if len(myPoints) != 0:
        try:
            contour = myPoints[:17]
            left_eye = myPoints[36:42]
            right_eye = myPoints[42:48]
            lips = myPoints[48:61]
            
            final_image = draw_lines(final_image,contour)
            final_image = draw_lines(final_image,left_eye)
            final_image = draw_lines(final_image,right_eye)
            final_image = draw_lines(final_image,lips)


        except:
            pass

    cv2.imwrite(r'final_image.jpg', final_image)

feature_Detection('face.jpg')



```

28/11/21, 9:57â€¯am - Pooja: def estimate_kernel(del_B, del_S, gamma = 1, lr = 0.1, epochs = 10, tol = 1e-10):
    
    k = np.random.rand(3,3)
    k = k/np.sum(k)

    for i in range(epochs):
        print(f"EPOCH : {i} k : \n{k}")
        
        # 1024 - 1022
        val1 = convolve(del_S, flip_matrix(k))
        
        # 1022 - 1022
        val2 = val1 - del_B

        # 1022 - 3
        val3 = convolve(del_S, val2)

        del_k = 2 * (val3 + gamma*k)
        
        if (del_k < tol).all():
            break

        k = k - lr * del_k
        k = k/np.sum(k)

zhang_img_list_vis = []
three_degree_points=[]
two_degree_points=[]

## creating a 3d coordinate system of the world
x,y=np.meshgrid(range(8),range(6))
world_coords=np.hstack((x.reshape(48,1),y.reshape(48,1),np.zeros((48,1)))).astype('float32')
print(world_coords.shape)
print(world_coords)

c = 0
for row in checkerboard_image_list:
  for img in row:
    c += 1
    flag,corners = cv2.findChessboardCorners(img , (8,6))

    two_degree_points.append(corners)
Flag, K_z, dist, R_vecs, T_vecs = cv2.calibrateCamera(three_degree_points, two_degree_points, (checkerboard_image_list[0][0].shape[1],checkerboard_image_list[0][0].shape[0]), None, None)
def eulerAnglesToRotationMatrix(theta) :
    R_x = np.array([[1,0,0],[0,math.cos(theta[0]),-math.sin(theta[0])],[0,math.sin(theta[0]), math.cos(theta[0])]])
    R_y = np.array([[math.cos(theta[1]),0,math.sin(theta[1])],[0,1,0],[-math.sin(theta[1]),0,math.cos(theta[1])]])             
    R_z = np.array([[math.cos(theta[2]),-math.sin(theta[2]),0],[math.sin(theta[2]),math.cos(theta[2]),0],[0,0,1]])
    R = np.dot(R_z,np.dot(R_y,R_x))
    return R

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3,5, figsize = (15,15))
for i in range(len(three_degree_points)):

    R_z = eulerAnglesToRotationMatrix(R_vecs[i])
    Ext = np.hstack((R_z , T_vecs[i]))

    P_z = np.dot(K_z, Ext)
    P_z = P_z/P_z[-1,-1]

    
    #get world coordinates for the image
    world_coords_h = np.append(three_degree_points[i], np.ones((three_degree_points[i].shape[0],1)), axis=1)

    #get projected image points
    imgpoints_proj = np.dot(P_z, world_coords_h.T)
    imgpoints_proj = imgpoints_proj / imgpoints_proj[-1, :]

    
    actual_chessboard = checkerboard_image_list[i//5][i%5]
    
    #plortting the wireframe
    for j in range(0,6*8, 8):
        ax[i//5][i%5].plot(imgpoints_proj[0, j:j+8], imgpoints_proj[1,j:j+8], linestyle='-', 
                           marker='o', color='g', markersize=5)
    
    for j in range(8):
        xpts = [imgpoints_proj[0, j], imgpoints_proj[0, j+8], imgpoints_proj[0, j+8*2],
                imgpoints_proj[0, j+8*3], imgpoints_proj[0, j+8*4],imgpoints_proj[0, j+8*5]]
        
        ypts = [imgpoints_proj[1, j], imgpoints_proj[1, j+8], imgpoints_proj[1, j+8*2],
                imgpoints_proj[1, j+8*3], imgpoints_proj[1, j+8*4],imgpoints_proj[1, j+8*5]]
        
        ax[i//5][i%5].plot(xpts, ypts, linestyle='-', marker='o', color='g', markersize=5)

    ax[i//5][i%5].imshow(actual_chessboard)
```

image = cv2.imread("../images/left12.jpg")
plt.imshow(image)

world_coordinates = np.zeros((6*7,3), np.float32)
world_coordinates[:,:2] = np.mgrid[0:7,0:6].T.reshape(-1,2)

gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
ret, image_coordinates = cv2.findChessboardCorners(gray, (7,6), None)
image_coordinates.reshape(42,2)


world_coordinates = np.array(world_coordinates).astype("float32")
image_coordinates = np.array(image_coordinates).astype("float32")
world_coordinates = world_coordinates.reshape(1,42,3)
image_coordinates = image_coordinates.reshape(1,42,2)

ret, intrinsic_matrix, distortion, rotation, translation = cv2.calibrateCamera(world_coordinates,image_coordinates, (image.shape[1],image.shape[0]), None, None)
print("Distortion : ")
print(distortion)

#refining the camera matrix
newcameramtx, roi = cv2.getOptimalNewCameraMatrix(intrinsic_matrix,distortion,(image.shape[1],image.shape[0]),1,(image.shape[1],image.shape[0]))
x, y, w, h = roi

h,  w = image.shape[:2]

# undistort
mapx, mapy = cv2.initUndistortRectifyMap(intrinsic_matrix, distortion, None, newcameramtx, (w,h), 5)
dst = cv2.remap(image, mapx, mapy, cv2.INTER_LINEAR)
# crop the image
x, y, w, h = roi
print(roi)
dst = dst[y:y+h, x:x+w]

plt.imshow(dst)

22/03/22, 4:55â€¯am - Pooja: https://github.com/coder-mano/Shi-Tomasi-Corner-Detector/blob/master/Implementation/Main.py
22/03/22, 5:47â€¯am - Pooja: https://sandipanweb.wordpress.com/2018/02/25/implementing-lucas-kanade-optical-flow-algorithm-in-python/
22/03/22, 8:19â€¯am - mehul mathur: def LukasKanadeForwardAdditive(image_1, image_2, window_size):
    assert image_1.shape == image_2.shape, "shape of 'image_1' and 'image_2' should be same"
    assert len(image_1.shape) == 2, "image must be grayscale"
    assert window_size[0] % 2 == 1, "'windowSize[0]' should be odd"
    assert window_size[1] % 2 == 1, "'windowSize[1]' should be odd"
    
    image_1 = image_1.astype(float)
    image_2 = image_2.astype(float)
    
    tao = 0.01
    dx = np.array([[-1, 1],
                   [-1, 1]])
    dy = np.array([[1, 1],
                   [-1, -1]])
    dt = np.array([[1, 1],
                   [1, 1]])
    
    # Compute derivative
    Ix = convolve2d(image_1, dx, mode='same') + convolve2d(image_2,  dx, mode='same')
    Iy = convolve2d(image_1, dy, mode='same') + convolve2d(image_2,  dy, mode='same')
    It = convolve2d(image_1, dt, mode='same') + convolve2d(image_2,  -dt, mode='same')
    
    # Find keypoints
    corners = cv2.goodFeaturesToTrack((image_1 * 255).astype(np.uint8), 1000, 0.01, 10)
    
    # Solve LK equations for each keypoint to get flow
    u = np.zeros(image_1.shape)
    v = np.zeros(image_1.shape)
    selected = np.zeros(image_1.shape, dtype=bool)
    for corner in corners:
        A = np.zeros((2, 2))
        b = np.zeros(2)
        x, y = corner[0].astype(int)
        
        l = x - window_size[0] // 2
        r = x + window_size[0] // 2+1
        t = y - window_size[1] // 2
        b = y + window_size[1] // 2+1
        if l < 0 or r > image_1.shape[1] or t < 0 or b > image_1.shape[0]:
            # Window falls out of range
            continue

        ix = Ix[t:b,l:r].flatten()
        iy = Iy[t:b,l:r].flatten()
        it = It[t:b,l:r].flatten()

        A = np.c_[ix, iy]
        b = it
        AtA = A.T @ A
        if np.min(np.linalg.eig(AtA)[0]) < tao:
            # Flow can't be calculated accurately
            continue
        inv = np.linalg.pinv(AtA)
        uv = inv @ A.T @ b
        u[y,x], v[y,x] = uv
        selected[y,x] = True
    
    return u, v, selected

13/04/22, 1:57â€¯am - mehul mathur: ```
class Autoencoder(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self , model_type):
        super(Autoencoder, self).__init__()
        # Input size: [batch, 3, 32, 32]
        # Output size: [batch, 3, 32, 32]
        if model_type == 'fc':
          self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
              nn.Flatten(),
              nn.Linear(3*32*32 , 1024),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(1024 , 256),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(256 , 32),
          )
          self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
              nn.Linear(32 , 256),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(256 , 1024),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(1024 , 3*32*32),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Unflatten(1, torch.Size([3, 32, 32])),
              nn.Sigmoid()
          )
        elif model_type == 'fc_conv':
          self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
              # Write your code here
              nn.Conv2d(3, 12, 4, stride=2, padding=1),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Conv2d(12 , 32 , 4 , stride=2 , padding=1),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Flatten(),
              nn.Linear(32*8*8 , 256),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(256 , 32)

          )
          self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
              # Write your code here
              nn.Linear(32 , 256),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(256 , 32*8*8),
              nn.Unflatten(1 , torch.Size([32, 8, 8])),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.ConvTranspose2d(32, 12, 4, stride=2, padding=1),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.ConvTranspose2d(12, 3 , 4 , stride=2 , padding=1),
              nn.Sigmoid()
          )
        elif model_type == 'conv':
          self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
              # Write your code here
              nn.Conv2d(3, 12, 4, stride=2, padding=1),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Conv2d(12 , 32 , 4 , stride=2 , padding=1),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Conv2d(32 , 64 , 4 , stride=2 , padding=1),
              nn.Flatten(),
              nn.Linear(32*8*8 , 256),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(256 , 32)

          )
          self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
              # Write your code here
              nn.Linear(32 , 256),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.Linear(256 , 32*8*8),
              nn.Unflatten(1 , torch.Size([32, 8, 8])),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.ConvTranspose2d(32, 12, 4, stride=2, padding=1),
              nn.ReLU(),
              nn.ConvTranspose2d(12, 3 , 4 , stride=2 , padding=1),
              nn.Sigmoid()
          )
    def forward(self, x):
        encoded = self.encoder(x)
        decoded = self.decoder(encoded)
        return encoded, decoded

```

13/04/22, 12:26â€¯pm - mehul mathur: ```
#### Applications:
- Black and White to colour images
- Restoring corrupted or dirty images (Image Denoising)
- Missing Value Imputation
- Dimensionality Reduction

#### Types
- Undercomplete Autoencoders
- Sparse Autoencoders
- Denoising Autoencoders
- Deep Autoencoders
```
13/04/22, 12:26â€¯pm - mehul mathur: ```
- **PCA** - Can only do linear mapping to lower dimensions <br> **AE** - Can learn non linear transformations to lower dimensions due to the activation functions
- **PCA** - PCA features are totally linearly uncorrelated with each other since features are projections onto the orthogonal basis <br> **AE** - Features can be correlated with each other
- **PCA** - Simple Linear mapping <br> **AE** - Prone to overfitting
```

25/04/22, 7:28â€¯am - mehul mathur: # 

- Setup and ran initial code on ADA
- Trained and got few outputs (the bulldozer model and others)
    - **How nerf works**
        - Nerf is basically a overfitted function model which takes input 5 parameters-
            - X - X world coordinate
            - Y - Y World coordinate
            - Z - Z world coordinate
            - Theta and Phi - Camera position (or orienation angles from which the model is viewed)
            
        - It outputs the RGB color and the density - sigma (alpha value)
        - So using the weights of such a model a 3d object can be recreated from any angle
    - **Implementation**
        - Create a Deep cnn network which initially takes in the 3 coordinates x,y,z as input and outputs just the density and a 256 dimenstional vector
        - Using both of these concatenate with the orientation angles to also give the color values - RGB
        - Used pytorch
- Currently implementing code for ray sampling and collecting pictures of real objects in iiith
    - **Sampling along the ray**
        - Two train the model , given some sparse collection of images of the 3d object , a ray is passsed perpendicularly through each pixel of each image
        - Along this ray points are sampled - Each point is (x , y , z) and theta and phi (angle orientation of the ray)
        - The output at each point is obtained - RGB , alpha
        - Then these values are integrated along the ray to obtain one color of that pixel
        - Then this color is compared with the ground truth one (difference) and then this loss is backpropogated
- Converting these real life images to data to be inputted in the model
25/04/22, 7:32â€¯am - mehul mathur: for naren:
Setup and ran code on ada
Trained and got few outputs (the bulldozer model and others)
Currently implementing code for ray sampling and collecting pictures of real objects in iiith
Converting these images to data to be inputted in the model
